<item>
  <title>On the Rank and the Span Rank of Modules</title>
  <dc:creator>sun123zxy </dc:creator>
  <link>https://blog.sun123zxy.top/posts/20251118-rank/</link>
  <description><![CDATA[ We work over a commutative ring <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?R"> with unity. The rank <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%5Coperatorname%7Brank%7D_R%20M"> of a module <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?R">-module <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M"> is defined as the maximal cardinality of a <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?R">-linearly independent subset of <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?M">. A homologist might write this as an exact sequence <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?%0A0%20%5Clongrightarrow%20R%5E%7B%5Coplus%20n%7D%20%5Clongrightarrow%20M%0A"> where <img src="https://latex.codecogs.com/png.latex?n"> is as large as possible. ]]></description>
  <category>math</category>
  <category>algebra</category>
  <category>commalg</category>
  <guid>https://blog.sun123zxy.top/posts/20251118-rank/</guid>
  <pubDate>Tue, 18 Nov 2025 00:00:00 GMT</pubDate>
</item>
